  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Considering Backend Framework Options**\n\nI\'m currently evaluating potential backend frameworks. FastAPI seems like a strong contender, given its speed and modern design. It aligns well with the potential needs. I\'m also considering the data population for the workspaces displayed in the preview. I am trying to determine where this data is sourced from; is it static or dynamically generated?\n\n\n**Re-evaluating Backend Assumptions**\n\nI\'m reconsidering the backend framework strategy. While FastAPI is appealing, the current setup uses Node.js with an Express server, or a client-side SPA. This means FastAPI might not be the most compatible solution at this time, since the frontend is currently set up for a Node.js-based environment.\n\n\n**Planning Scalability for the Future**\n\nI\'m thinking about the implications of a separate FastAPI backend. If we go that route, I envision hosting it as a distinct microservice, possibly on Cloud Run, and connecting it to the React frontend through API requests. It\'s a scalable solution, especially for those computationally intensive processes like AI. We don\'t need to implement it now, but it\'s a valuable option to keep in mind. Also, I\'ve got more insight into how workspaces are populated.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "### Thoughts on a FastAPI Backend\n\n**FastAPI** is a superb choice for a educational or AI-driven copilot backend. Here is how it compares and why it fits well into a professional architecture:\n\n* **Why it fits:** FastAPI is built on Python, which is the gold standard for AI, machine learning, and structured data science libraries. If you want to integrate complex NLP, custom document parsers, or vector databases (like ChromaDB or pgvector) down the road, Python\'s ecosystem is unmatched.\n* **Key Benefits:** It provides automatic interactive API documentation (Swagger/OpenAPI), high performance through asynchronous execution (`async`/`await`), and strict schema validation using Pydantic.\n* **Production Deployment:** Since the current AI Studio container runs a Node.js/React environment on port `3000`, a production setup would run FastAPI as a separate microservice (for example, on Google Cloud Run) and point your React frontend\'s fetch requests to that endpoint. \n\n---\n\n### How Your Current Data is Populated\n\nExcellent observation! The workspaces and students you see when first loading the preview are structured as follows:\n\n1. **Initial Hydration (`/src/defaultData.ts`)**: On first load, the app bootstraps a rich set of mock diagnostic data containing default classes (such as *Grade 10 Mathematics Standard*), realistic students (like *Sofia Patel* and *Aarav Sharma*), exam score history charts, and syllabus lesson notes.\n2. **Persistent Local State (`localStorage`)**: Once initialized, any changes you make in the UI\342\200\224such as adding a student, recording a test score, uploading manual homework logs, or creating a new workspace\342\200\224are immediately saved to your browser\'s persistent storage. \n3. **Subsequent visits**: The application automatically checks `localStorage` first. If modified records exist, it loads your custom workspace layout; otherwise, it degrades gracefully back to the template data."
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 3
      nanos: 738454488
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
